<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-318-065  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 318 065.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Jan 16 1989 n296 p61(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Next technology grasps emerging standard. (Hardware's new wave)(part 1)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Senia, Al.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Whether the new workstation from Next Inc will be a dazzlingtechnological breakthrough or a slick, over-priced rewrite ofcurrent technology depends on the point of view taken.andP;  Criticismsof Next include: use of the outdated 68030 microprocessor;distribution only to the education market; and price, as theworkstation will likely cost the same as low-end, faster RISCmachines once the education discount is dropped.andP;  Others, though,laud Next as the first commodity workstation using a transparentuser interface, the NextStep software architecture.andP;  Seen this waythe Next machine is the first workstation with a mainframecomputing architecture.andP;  The CPU exists only as an entry point forthe user.andP;  The simple object-oriented programming environment isextended to the interface, simplifying operation and allowing lessdirect access to the source code because developers write for theinterface, not the screen.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   NeXT Inc. (innovations).andO;Product:   Next (Workstation) (design and construction)NeXTstep (Operating system) (design and construction).andO;Topic:     User-FriendlinessApplications ProgrammingObject-Oriented LanguagesWorkstationsNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Steve Jobs. (portrait)Person:    Jobs, Steven (innovations).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>